    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Dorsally flattened with eight shell plates articulating dorsally, surrounded by a soft fleshy girdle. Shell plates very even and rectangular with smooth, rounded edges. Shell texture with forwardly converging rows of granules along the areas aside the centre, leading to a minutely granulated, finer pattern towards the middle, while growth-lines surround the shell. Girdle with scales, clearly ribbed in 3-6 rows. Articulamentum white or blue with wide, rounded anterior extensions. Colour brown or pale white.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_6155",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Small, typically around 5-15 mm total body length.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_6156",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Islands of the Atlantic Ocean as well as South Africa and southern Angola.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Saldanha Bay to False Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_6157",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Under stones in the littoral zone.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_6158",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Herbivorous - rasps algae off the rocks using its radula.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_6159",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>External fertilization, but eggs retained in the pallial fold between the animal’s foot and surrounding fleshy part where the eggs are brooded and grow until juveniles are ready to be independent.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_6160",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>This is one of three brooding species that occur in the same region, but the other two, the Brooding chiton <i>Radsia nigrovirescens </i>and the Ribbed-shell chiton <i>Rhyssoplax crawfordi </i>have utterly different appearances and colour and cannot be confused. In the same genus, <i>I. elizabethensis, I. oniscus </i>and <i>I. textilis</i> co-occur, but all display much smoother or finer scales smooth to the naked eye. <i>I. bergoti </i>has more elevated valves and more prominent growth lines, but the biggest difference is in the clear ribbing on the girdle scales of <i>I. bergoti</i> which is absent or much reduced in the other species of the genus.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_6161",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
